#compdef orbitdb-relay-pinner
# ============================================================================
# orbitdb-relay-pinner - OrbitDB relay + pinning/sync
#   service for Helia/libp2p stacks (TypeScript -> Node,
#   MIT)
#
# Author : NiKrause
# Upstream: https://github.com/NiKrause/orbitdb-relay-pinner
# npm    : orbitdb-relay-pinner
#
# `orbitdb-relay-pinner` is a daemon that runs an
# OrbitDB-compatible libp2p circuit-relay-v2 node, pins
# replicated OrbitDB databases for clients, and provides
# the QUIC + WebRTC + TCP + WebSocket transports needed
# for peer connectivity. The daemon is configured almost
# entirely via environment variables (see `.env.example`
# at upstream for the full ~40-knob list); the CLI
# surface is intentionally minimal.
#
# Usage:
#   orbitdb-relay-pinner [--test]
#
# Flags:
#   --test                  - run in self-test mode
#                              (validates config + exits)
#
# Environment variables (most-common subset):
#   RELAY_TCP_PORT          - TCP listener port (default 9091)
#   RELAY_WS_PORT           - WebSocket listener port (default 9092)
#   RELAY_QUIC_PORT         - QUIC listener port (default 9094)
#   RELAY_WEBRTC_PORT       - WebRTC listener port (default 9093)
#   RELAY_LISTEN_IPV4       - IPv4 listen address (default 0.0.0.0)
#   RELAY_LISTEN_IPV6       - IPv6 listen address (default ::)
#   RELAY_DISABLE_IPV6      - disable IPv6 (default false)
#   RELAY_DISABLE_QUIC      - disable QUIC transport (default false)
#   RELAY_DISABLE_WEBRTC    - disable WebRTC transport (default false)
#   RELAY_DISABLE_BOOTSTRAP - skip public libp2p
#                              bootstrap peers
#   RELAY_REQUIRE_ORBITDB_HEADS_PROTOCOL
#                           - reject peers that don't
#                              advertise /orbitdb/heads/*
#                              (default false)
#   RELAY_CIRCUIT_HOP_TIMEOUT_MS
#                           - hop timeout (ms; default
#                              300000)
#   RELAY_CIRCUIT_MAX_RESERVATIONS
#                           - max simultaneous reservations
#                              (default 10000)
#   RELAY_STOP_TIMEOUT_MS   - graceful shutdown timeout
#                              (default 20000)
#   PUBLIC_IP               - public IP for announce-addr
#                              rewriting
#   VITE_APPEND_ANNOUNCE    - additional announce
#                              multiaddrs (comma-separated)
#
# Signal handling:
#   SIGINT / SIGTERM        - graceful shutdown (second
#                              signal forces immediate
#                              exit)
#
# The @chainsafe/libp2p-quic lane is built on
# `@chainsafe/libp2p-quic ^1.1.3` (declared at upstream
# package.json HEAD as a direct dep, used as one of the
# libp2p transports configured by `startRelay()`), the
# canonical Node libp2p QUIC transport by ChainSafe -
# github.com/ChainSafe/js-libp2p-quic. The package is
# a napi-rs binding to the underlying Rust quinn-rs
# QUIC stack (specifically a ChainSafe fork tuned for
# the libp2p use case: client + server roles per
# connection, bidirectional streams as the default
# multiplex primitive, qlog telemetry for debugging
# libp2p peer connectivity issues).
#
# This makes the Node QUIC slot's canonical library a
# *napi-rs binding to the same Rust quinn-rs stack that
# powers Axis 249's Rust slot*. The Node binding inherits
# quinn's RFC 9000 conformance + congestion-control
# implementations + rustls crypto backend; the napi-rs
# layer adds JS-callable APIs + zero-runtime-overhead
# guarantees + cross-platform pre-built binaries (Linux
# x64 / arm64 / musl, macOS x64 / arm64, Windows x64).
#
# orbitdb-relay-pinner uses @chainsafe/libp2p-quic as
# one of the four bundled libp2p transports (alongside
# TCP, WebSocket, and WebRTC). Each transport listens
# on its own port + each peer dial tries all configured
# transports concurrently, with the first-to-succeed
# winning. QUIC is the preferred transport for peer-to-
# peer connectivity through NATs because its UDP-based
# transport + connection-migration semantics survive
# IP changes that would break TCP-based connections.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 249 :: QUIC / RFC 9000 (UDP-based transport with
#              TLS 1.3 integrated + multiplexed streams)
# Round 1447 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 249
#                                       (242nd axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : quinn-rs/quinn              [R1445 _quicssh-rs]
#   Go      : quic-go/quic-go             [R1446 _qw]
#   TS/Node : @chainsafe/libp2p-quic      [R1447 THIS FILE]
#             (napi-rs binding to quinn-rs)
#
# @chainsafe/libp2p-quic closes Axis 249 with the *napi-
# rs-binding-to-the-Rust-slot* pattern. The three lanes
# form a clean spectrum of QUIC implementation strategies:
#
#   - Rust (quinn-rs/quinn): native Rust implementation;
#     sans-I/O `quinn-proto` state machine + tokio-async
#     `quinn` wrapper; rustls or openssl crypto backend;
#     BBR / NewReno / Cubic congestion control
#   - Go (quic-go/quic-go): native Go implementation
#     by Marten Seemann (former Chrome QUIC team);
#     stdlib crypto/tls QUIC integration since Go 1.21;
#     NewReno default + experimental Cubic
#   - Node (@chainsafe/libp2p-quic): napi-rs binding to
#     ChainSafe's fork of quinn-rs, tuned for the
#     libp2p use case; inherits quinn's RFC 9000
#     conformance + crypto stack; adds zero-runtime-
#     overhead JS bindings + cross-platform pre-built
#     binaries
#
# This Node-binds-to-Rust pattern echoes the @node-rs/
# argon2 pattern from Axis 244 (Node binds to RustCrypto
# argon2) and the napi-rs Snappy/XXHash patterns from
# earlier axes - the Node ecosystem increasingly leans
# on napi-rs as the standard cross-platform binding
# mechanism for performance-sensitive primitives that
# already have mature Rust implementations.
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - the
# IETF QUIC interop matrix validates that quinn + quic-
# go + @chainsafe/libp2p-quic (and msquic + ngtcp2 +
# quiche + lsquic) talk to each other across all RFC
# 9000 features. The qlog telemetry format (RFC 9369
# draft) provides a cross-impl debug log format.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - quicssh-rs (Rust, quinn): SSH-over-QUIC proxy
#     bypassing TCP-22-blocking middleboxes
#   - qw / quicwire (Go, quic-go): QUIC CONNECT-IP
#     mesh-VPN agent for layer-3 networking with
#     connection-migration semantics
#   - orbitdb-relay-pinner (Node, @chainsafe/libp2p-
#     quic): libp2p circuit-relay-v2 daemon using QUIC
#     as one of four parallel transports for NAT-
#     traversal peer-to-peer connectivity
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (SSH-over-QUIC
# proxy / IP-layer mesh VPN / p2p relay-pin daemon),
# three implementation strategies (native Rust /
# native Go / napi-rs binding to Rust), all converging
# on RFC 9000 wire-format compatibility.
#
# Axis 249 closes the round 1447 cycle - 242nd axis closed
# total.
# ============================================================================

_orbitdb-relay-pinner() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '--test[run in self-test mode (validate config + exit)]' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[print version]'
}

_orbitdb-relay-pinner "$@"
